# Getting Started with TeamViewer Remote Assistance

_Using TeamViewer QuickSupport _

## What is TeamViewer?

TeamViewer is a free program used to provide remote support and technical assistance. This convenient remote support software enables our support technicians to access your computer over the internet. This service is fully secure, and remote support can only be performed with your express permission and prior arrangement. As such, TeamViewer can be a useful alternative to arranging an on-site visit by one of our staff.

This guide describes how to download and run TeamViewer QuickSupport in order to initiate a remote support session.

_Note: The screenshots in this guide were captured using TeamViewer 11. If you are using a later version, the options may look slightly different; however, the basic procedure is the same for all recent versions of Teamviewer._

## Arranging Remote Support

Prior to downloading and connecting to a remote support session, the first thing you will need to do is contact us and arrange a time for your session to take place.

**For security reasons, we will never contact you for unsolicited remote support, or otherwise connect to your computer without prior arrangement.** If you are ever contacted by any person or company offering unsolicited remote support, it is generally best to decline. Allowing unsolicited remote connections to your computer represents a threat to the security of your computer and your identity.

## Using QuickSupport for PC (Windows)

Downloading and Running TeamViewer

Prior to beginning your remote support session, the TeamViewer program will first need to be downloaded and run from your computer. While TeamViewer QuickSupport is available for Windows, Mac, and Linux computers, for your convenience, the link below will automatically detect which version is best for your device.

To download TeamViewer QuickSupport, [click here](http://go.nerdoncloud.com/teamviewer). Alternatively, copy and paste the following link into your browser&#39;s address bar: [**http://go.nerdoncloud.com/teamviewer**](http://go.nerdoncloud.com/teamviewer).

Depending upon the operating system and browser you use, you may be prompted to either run the file or save it. In this particular example we are using Windows and Google Chrome. For other operating systems, the options may look slightly different; however, the basic procedure is the same on almost every computer.

After the download finishes, locate it in the bar at the bottom of the window. Click the **arrow** to the right of TeamViewerQS\_en.exe, and select **Show in folder**.

![](/docs/img/teamviewer-win-show-folder.png)

From the folder that appears, **move** the file by dragging and dropping it onto your **Desktop**. Close the folder window If desired.

Next, **right-click** the downloaded file and choose **Run as administrator**.

![](docs/img/teamviewer-win-as-admin.png)

Then, click **Run** to accept the security warning.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

If a User Account Control window appears, click **Yes** , and provide an administrator password if needed.

Establishing a TeamViewer Session

The TeamViewer window will now appear. Note the **green light** towards the bottom of the window, as well as the status, &quot;Ready to connect (secure connection).&quot; This indicates that TeamViewer is now able to accept an incoming remote support offer.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Make a note of **your ID** and the four-digit temporary **password** (obscured), which the support staff will need in order to securely connect to your computer.

Once the support technician has this information, they can take control of your computer. You will be able to see every action they perform, so do not be alarmed to see the mouse cursor moving and windows opening and closing. While the technician has control over the mouse and keyboard, you can still override their actions by moving your own mouse or using the keyboard yourself. This is useful in certain situations, such as entering passwords, or when replicating an issue for support staff to resolve.

If at any point you wish to stop an ongoing support session, simply close the TeamViewer window to disconnect the technician from your computer.

Once the remote support session is over, TeamViewer will automatically return control of your computer to you.

Always close the TeamViewer application once the remote support session is finished. This ensures that no one can access your computer remotely unless TeamViewer is opened again.

Please note: Some customers may see a dialog advertising the paid edition of TeamViewer or a **sponsored session** dialog. This is an unfortunate limitation of the version of TeamViewer used by our support team to offer assistance at no cost to you; however, you may simply **close** these windows to continue using your computer, with no further action required.

For more information, or to arrange a remote support session, please email our dedicated support staff at [support@nerdoncloud.com](mailto:support@nerdoncloud.com).

For other operating systems, the options may look slightly different; however, the basic procedure is the same on almost every Mac.

After the download finishes, locate it in the bar at the bottom of the window Click the **arrow** to the right of TeamViewerQS.dmg, and select **Show in Finder**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In the Finder window that appears double-click **TeamViewerQS.dmg** to open it.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Next, double-click the **QuickSupport icon** to open it when prompted.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

If prompted, click **Open** to accept the security warning. Provide an administrator password if necessary.
